Step-by-step reasoning:
• Key psychological mechanisms: Participants use observed outcomes (expected rewards from forced/free plays) to gauge the value of each option. In longer horizon games (more free choices) they are more inclined to explore, which effectively increases the weight given to differences in expected reward. In short horizon games, they rely more on immediate exploitation.
• Interaction: The model assumes that the utility difference between the two options is given by the difference in their observed expected rewards scaled by a sensitivity parameter. When the horizon is long, an added exploration bonus increases this effective sensitivity.
• Mathematical form: A linear model is used where the utility difference is a product of a “sensitivity” factor (which adds an exploration bonus in long horizon games) and the difference in expected rewards.
• Needed parameters: Two learnable parameters are used. One (beta_exploit) represents the baseline sensitivity for exploitation and the other (beta_explore) represents the additional sensitivity (exploration bonus) when there are many free choices (horizon = 6). Their bounds are set generously (e.g., [–100, 100]).
• Mapping to observable behavior: The computed utility difference, which is the model’s prediction, will later be transformed by a logistic function to generate a choice probability for the free‐choice trials. Our model directly predicts the utility (to be used later for probability mapping) on free-choice trials (where forced_choice == FALSE).

Below is the formal model specification.

<MODEL>
U = (beta_exploit + beta_explore * I_horizon) * (expected_reward1 - expected_reward0)
</MODEL>

